==History== In 2008, the '''''Dust Storm''''' was shown at Artropolis, [[Chicago]]. In 2011, it was shown at [[Perth Institute of Contemporary Arts|PICA]], Perth, Australia, [[Ivorypress]], Madrid, Spain, and [[Irish Museum of Modern Art]].
==Analysis== The 3D "hyperreal" portraits depict beautiful landscapes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.europeana.eu/portal/record/2063628/IRE_280_008.html|title=Dust Storm (Manter, Kansas)|website=www.europeana.eu|access-date=2016-04-28}}</ref> {{quote|Dust Storm unites a classic image from the Great Depression with a contemporary industrial landscape, setting them in a cosmological orbit that is completed over the full spectrum of a year. The exploitation of oil that goes back to the beginning of the 20th Century is presented as the catalyst of conditions that led to the ecological disaster of Dust Bowl. But nothing is didactic. The pity in the subject comes to viewers subliminally through a visual poem of complexity and power.<ref>http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-04-26/features/0804250596_1_folk-and-outsider-art-dust-storm-galleries</ref>}}
